1
00:01:48,241 --> 00:01:50,142
<i>You got any stories, friend?</i>

2
00:01:53,714 --> 00:01:56,684
Yeah, I suppose I do.

3
00:01:59,953 --> 00:02:02,479
You want to know the
saddest thing I ever saw?

4
00:02:03,290 --> 00:02:06,818
When I was a boy, my
brother and I wanted a dog.

5
00:02:07,628 --> 00:02:11,429
So, our father took
in an old greyhound.

6
00:02:12,532 --> 00:02:14,592
- Never seen a greyhound, have you?
- No.

7
00:02:15,302 --> 00:02:17,965
Seen a few showdowns in my day.

8
00:02:21,008 --> 00:02:23,443
A greyhound is a racing dog.

9
00:02:23,677 --> 00:02:25,646
It spends its life
running in circles,

10
00:02:26,279 --> 00:02:29,613
chasing a bit of felt
made up like a rabbit.

11
00:02:30,384 --> 00:02:32,819
One day, we took it to the park.

12
00:02:33,687 --> 00:02:36,782
Now, Dad had warned
us how fast that dog was,

13
00:02:37,124 --> 00:02:38,956
but we couldn't resist.

14
00:02:39,159 --> 00:02:41,128
So, my brother
took off the leash.

15
00:02:41,361 --> 00:02:46,561
And in that instant,
the dog spotted a cat.

16
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:49,970
I imagine it must have looked
just like that piece of felt.

17
00:02:51,972 --> 00:02:53,235
He ran.

18
00:02:55,509 --> 00:03:02,211
Never saw a thing as
beautiful as that old dog running.

19
00:03:04,484 --> 00:03:07,511
<i>Until at last, he
finally caught it.</i>

20
00:03:09,022 --> 00:03:13,551
And to the horror of
everyone, he killed that little cat.

21
00:03:13,860 --> 00:03:15,829
Tore it to pieces.

22
00:03:16,496 --> 00:03:19,864
Then he just sat
there, confused.

23
00:03:22,903 --> 00:03:29,434
That dog had spent its whole
life trying to catch that thing.

24
00:03:32,145 --> 00:03:34,705
Now it had no idea what to do.

25
00:03:39,119 --> 00:03:41,850
That is one humdinger
of a story, partner.

26
00:03:42,889 --> 00:03:46,053
Shall we drink to the
lady with the white shoes?

27
00:04:18,892 --> 00:04:19,985
<i>Find me.</i>

28
00:04:21,895 --> 00:04:22,895
<i>Show me how.</i>

29
00:04:26,800 --> 00:04:29,326
There she is. Pariah.

30
00:04:29,770 --> 00:04:34,401
City of outcasts, delinquents,
thieves, whores, and murderers.

31
00:04:34,641 --> 00:04:35,665
Once we cross the gates,

32
00:04:35,909 --> 00:04:40,005
you will reap the full benefits of El
Lazo's gratitude for my safe return.

33
00:04:49,456 --> 00:04:50,515
Are you all right?

34
00:04:51,258 --> 00:04:52,453
Of course.

35
00:04:54,127 --> 00:04:55,425
Did I do something wrong?

36
00:04:56,496 --> 00:04:58,829
Just earlier, I thought I
heard you talking to someone.

37
00:05:00,033 --> 00:05:01,865
Must have been the wind.

38
00:05:18,718 --> 00:05:20,016
Come on.

39
00:05:22,222 --> 00:05:23,383
<i>This way.</i>

40
00:05:42,042 --> 00:05:43,452
<i>The farther up we
get from Sweetwater,</i>

41
00:05:43,476 --> 00:05:47,004
the more grandiose, the
bigger the narratives become.

42
00:05:48,748 --> 00:05:50,683
It's beautiful in its own way.

43
00:05:50,851 --> 00:05:53,082
For once, I agree.

44
00:05:53,253 --> 00:05:55,552
Some of the park feels like it
was designed by committee,

45
00:05:55,755 --> 00:05:59,886
market-tested, but everything
out here is more raw.

46
00:06:01,161 --> 00:06:02,891
<i>But it doesn't come cheap.</i>

47
00:06:03,063 --> 00:06:05,191
<i>Rumor is, they are
hemorrhaging cash.</i>

48
00:06:05,365 --> 00:06:07,527
<i>We're considering
buying them out.</i>

49
00:06:07,901 --> 00:06:11,167
Supposedly, this place was
all started by a partnership,

50
00:06:11,371 --> 00:06:15,206
and then right before the park
opened, one of the partners killed himself.

51
00:06:15,508 --> 00:06:17,534
<i>It sent the park
into a free fall.</i>

52
00:06:17,878 --> 00:06:20,871
I mean, I don't know any of the
details. I don't even know his name.

53
00:06:21,047 --> 00:06:23,159
You must have a team of
lawyers looking at this place.

54
00:06:23,183 --> 00:06:25,880
Yeah, well, they came up empty.

55
00:06:26,052 --> 00:06:28,612
<i>He's a complete mystery.
Not even a picture.</i>

56
00:06:28,922 --> 00:06:30,914
<i>Well, whoever
designed this place,</i>

57
00:06:31,124 --> 00:06:34,060
you get the feeling they don't
think very much of people.

58
00:06:36,863 --> 00:06:38,331
Who are they?

59
00:06:39,799 --> 00:06:42,268
They call themselves
the Army of New Virginia.

60
00:06:42,469 --> 00:06:44,904
<i>Everyone else calls
them the Confederados.</i>

61
00:06:45,105 --> 00:06:47,631
My father told me about them.

62
00:06:47,807 --> 00:06:51,403
Ex-Confederate soldiers that
refused to surrender after the war.

63
00:06:51,578 --> 00:06:53,513
<i>Now they work as
mercenaries below the border.</i>

64
00:06:53,680 --> 00:06:55,160
<i>They are the key to this game.</i>

65
00:06:55,515 --> 00:06:56,915
What game?

66
00:06:57,083 --> 00:06:58,574
The biggest game there is.

67
00:06:58,752 --> 00:06:59,981
War.

68
00:07:00,153 --> 00:07:01,797
Supposedly, it's at the
far reaches of the park.

69
00:07:01,821 --> 00:07:05,451
Now, I've never made it that
far, but this could be our chance.

70
00:07:07,460 --> 00:07:10,589
<i>I've known plenty of truly
fucked-up individuals in my time.</i>

71
00:07:10,830 --> 00:07:13,800
Few that'd hold a candle
to you, sure. But this one?

72
00:07:13,967 --> 00:07:17,529
<i>Theodore Flood?
He was Wyatt's friend.</i>

73
00:07:18,438 --> 00:07:22,808
You know, his former associations
are exactly why we need him.

74
00:07:23,009 --> 00:07:26,468
He's gonna lead me
straight to the big bad wolf.

75
00:07:26,646 --> 00:07:27,841
I wouldn't count on that.

76
00:07:29,816 --> 00:07:31,546
Aw, shit.

77
00:07:44,230 --> 00:07:46,358
Didn't take you for
the charitable type.

78
00:07:46,566 --> 00:07:48,865
You should have left
him on that tree to die.

79
00:07:51,338 --> 00:07:53,330
You believe in fate, Lawrence?

80
00:07:53,740 --> 00:07:55,231
<i>If the bitch exists,</i>

81
00:07:55,475 --> 00:07:57,376
I'd like to kick her in
the teeth about now.

82
00:07:57,577 --> 00:08:00,979
Don't be so glib.
You'll hurt my feelings.

83
00:08:02,048 --> 00:08:04,415
As another old friend
of mine likes to say,

84
00:08:04,651 --> 00:08:09,055
"There's a path for everyone.
Your path leads you back to me."

85
00:08:09,889 --> 00:08:12,882
Do you ever wonder why I've
kept you with me this whole journey?

86
00:08:13,193 --> 00:08:16,561
Maybe you like the pleasure of
my company, you sadistic fuck.

87
00:08:18,898 --> 00:08:20,423
Maybe I do.

88
00:08:21,568 --> 00:08:25,198
There's not a man in the world who
would take the tone with me you do.

89
00:08:25,705 --> 00:08:28,038
In a past life, perhaps.

90
00:08:30,010 --> 00:08:33,037
Teddy here is not
looking long for this world.

91
00:08:33,413 --> 00:08:35,439
Nearest healer is in Pariah.

92
00:08:35,715 --> 00:08:38,116
But ain't no way he's
gonna make it that far.

93
00:08:38,351 --> 00:08:40,183
He's lost too much blood.

94
00:08:40,387 --> 00:08:41,548
<i>Are you lost?</i>

95
00:08:47,527 --> 00:08:50,554
Our friend here is a
little worse for the wear.

96
00:08:52,432 --> 00:08:54,264
Any water nearby, son?

97
00:08:54,901 --> 00:08:57,200
There's a creek on the
other side of the canyon.

98
00:08:57,937 --> 00:08:59,405
Fetch us some, would you?

99
00:09:01,408 --> 00:09:02,899
Now, hurry.

100
00:09:03,610 --> 00:09:06,205
Our friend here needs
some if he's going to make it.

101
00:09:06,479 --> 00:09:07,777
Get.

102
00:09:11,484 --> 00:09:12,645
Eh.

103
00:09:13,486 --> 00:09:14,749
Too small.

104
00:09:15,722 --> 00:09:17,088
What does that mean?

105
00:09:17,390 --> 00:09:19,621
And what are you
sending him for water for?

106
00:09:19,959 --> 00:09:22,292
I'm the one you made fill up
the sow's bag this morning.

107
00:09:32,338 --> 00:09:33,538
<i>A shame, really.</i>

108
00:09:34,607 --> 00:09:37,600
I always enjoy our
time together, Lawrence.

109
00:09:37,777 --> 00:09:39,337
What the fuck is that
supposed to mean?

110
00:09:40,647 --> 00:09:43,412
It means I was wrong.

111
00:09:44,117 --> 00:09:47,576
The path that brought
you here, it wasn't for me.

112
00:09:48,521 --> 00:09:50,012
It was for him.

113
00:10:02,435 --> 00:10:05,997
Sorry, Lawrence. Guess
I'll see you on the other side.

114
00:10:26,059 --> 00:10:27,152
Uh-oh.

115
00:10:27,360 --> 00:10:28,521
Not looking good for you.

116
00:10:28,795 --> 00:10:29,795
Closing.

117
00:10:29,963 --> 00:10:31,625
Forget it. I win.

118
00:10:31,898 --> 00:10:33,025
I always win!

119
00:10:34,968 --> 00:10:36,163
Not fair.

120
00:10:36,803 --> 00:10:39,466
All you had was a smashed
cheekbone and an ear.

121
00:10:39,706 --> 00:10:42,301
You know how hard it is to get
the auricle curves symmetrical?

122
00:10:42,575 --> 00:10:45,306
You had to, what, plug and
patch a couple bullet holes?

123
00:10:45,512 --> 00:10:47,003
And a knife wound.

124
00:10:48,214 --> 00:10:50,376
<i>It was a contained incision.</i>

125
00:10:50,650 --> 00:10:52,414
Almost like they were
looking for something.

126
00:10:57,023 --> 00:10:58,651
Are you fucking kidding me?

127
00:10:59,192 --> 00:11:02,856
You really think this little fuck
puppet's coming to get you? Huh?

128
00:11:03,096 --> 00:11:04,758
It got off the table and ran.

129
00:11:05,064 --> 00:11:07,024
That's 'cause you forgot
to put her in sleep mode.

130
00:11:07,167 --> 00:11:09,178
Yeah, I really think I
remembered to put her in sleep.

131
00:11:09,202 --> 00:11:11,569
You know, that's the
thing about forgetting.

132
00:11:11,738 --> 00:11:14,230
You think you
remembered, but you didn't.

133
00:11:16,176 --> 00:11:18,111
- Break time.
<i>- Yeah!</i>

134
00:11:19,112 --> 00:11:21,081
I've got a ham sandwich

135
00:11:21,247 --> 00:11:24,240
and a nubile redhead
loaded up in the VR tank,

136
00:11:24,417 --> 00:11:26,784
awaiting instruction.

137
00:11:29,422 --> 00:11:30,515
<i>Yeah.</i>

138
00:12:06,960 --> 00:12:08,485
Welcome back.

139
00:12:09,262 --> 00:12:12,790
Looks like a couple gallons of Lawrence
swirling around in you did you good.

140
00:12:14,734 --> 00:12:16,100
Ready to get back on the road?

141
00:12:17,637 --> 00:12:20,300
Merciful thing would
be to put a bullet in me.

142
00:12:20,573 --> 00:12:23,168
Whoever said I was merciful?

143
00:12:23,476 --> 00:12:25,411
And it's not my
fault you're suffering.

144
00:12:26,579 --> 00:12:28,571
You used to be beautiful.

145
00:12:28,982 --> 00:12:32,475
When this place started, I
opened one of you up once.

146
00:12:33,519 --> 00:12:35,613
Million little perfect pieces.

147
00:12:36,155 --> 00:12:37,919
And then they changed you.

148
00:12:38,157 --> 00:12:41,924
Made you this sad, real mess.

149
00:12:42,195 --> 00:12:44,858
Flesh and bone, just like us.

150
00:12:45,131 --> 00:12:48,363
They said it would
improve the park experience.

151
00:12:48,635 --> 00:12:51,036
But you know why
they really did it?

152
00:12:51,437 --> 00:12:52,996
It was cheaper.

153
00:12:54,474 --> 00:12:56,773
Your humanity is cost-effective.

154
00:12:57,310 --> 00:12:58,505
So was your suffering.

155
00:12:58,778 --> 00:13:01,612
Whatever it is you
want from me, mister,

156
00:13:03,283 --> 00:13:05,027
I ain't gonna be worth
a damn to you like this.

157
00:13:05,051 --> 00:13:06,917
Well, that would
be a shame, Teddy.

158
00:13:07,086 --> 00:13:11,023
After your misadventure,
Wyatt killed a settler family.

159
00:13:11,190 --> 00:13:12,852
Made off with their daughter.

160
00:13:13,059 --> 00:13:15,688
Girl, I think you know,

161
00:13:16,029 --> 00:13:17,156
name of Dolores.

162
00:13:22,402 --> 00:13:23,893
They have Dolores?

163
00:13:25,338 --> 00:13:26,499
There it is.

164
00:13:28,341 --> 00:13:30,606
The magic word. Come on.

165
00:13:37,083 --> 00:13:39,882
Hey! Much obliged there, son.

166
00:13:43,289 --> 00:13:45,121
Don't worry about him.

167
00:13:45,391 --> 00:13:47,622
Someone'll be
along for him shortly.

168
00:14:13,119 --> 00:14:14,678
Mommy!

169
00:14:16,923 --> 00:14:18,084
Are you all right?

170
00:14:26,666 --> 00:14:30,125
When I ran from home, I
told myself it was the only way.

171
00:14:32,238 --> 00:14:37,939
Lately, I've wondered if in every
moment there aren't many paths.

172
00:14:38,444 --> 00:14:39,742
Choices.

173
00:14:40,346 --> 00:14:41,780
Hanging in the air like ghosts.

174
00:14:41,948 --> 00:14:46,079
And if you could just see them,
you could change your whole life.

175
00:14:47,186 --> 00:14:50,156
Is that what you want? You
want to change your life?

176
00:14:50,356 --> 00:14:51,847
Doesn't everybody want that?

177
00:14:53,860 --> 00:14:55,522
I guess they do.

178
00:14:56,129 --> 00:14:58,325
Maybe that's why they come here.

179
00:14:59,532 --> 00:15:02,502
Whoever you were
before doesn't matter here.

180
00:15:03,436 --> 00:15:04,836
There's no rules
or restrictions.

181
00:15:05,705 --> 00:15:08,698
You can change the story of your
life. You can become someone else.

182
00:15:08,875 --> 00:15:12,368
No one will judge you. No one
in the real world will even know.

183
00:15:12,879 --> 00:15:14,356
The only thing holding
you back is yourself.

184
00:15:14,380 --> 00:15:15,380
What do you mean by that?

185
00:15:16,949 --> 00:15:19,509
You said, "No one in
the real world will know."

186
00:15:20,853 --> 00:15:23,288
I thought you weren't supposed
to notice things like that.

187
00:15:24,657 --> 00:15:26,023
Why wouldn't I?

188
00:15:28,294 --> 00:15:30,854
Recently, it seems
like the whole world

189
00:15:31,030 --> 00:15:34,797
is calling to me in a
way it hasn't before.

190
00:15:50,750 --> 00:15:52,790
Billy, where the hell
have you been? Come on.

191
00:15:54,187 --> 00:15:56,713
El Lazo's agreed to have an
audience with y'all tomorrow.

192
00:15:56,889 --> 00:15:59,484
In the meantime, there's
a brothel I recommend.

193
00:15:59,692 --> 00:16:01,251
<i>Ooh. They have a contortionist.</i>

194
00:16:01,494 --> 00:16:04,157
Oh, I don't think Dolores
would find that very interesting.

195
00:16:04,363 --> 00:16:06,992
Who the fuck cares
what Dolores wants?

196
00:16:07,166 --> 00:16:08,429
She's a goddamn doll!

197
00:16:08,601 --> 00:16:10,593
Can you not say that around her?

198
00:16:10,837 --> 00:16:14,501
I swear, I feel like
she understands.

199
00:16:15,741 --> 00:16:17,573
Of course you do.

200
00:16:56,582 --> 00:17:00,349
<i>May you rest in a deep
and dreamless slumber.</i>

201
00:17:08,594 --> 00:17:09,994
<i>Hello, Dolores.</i>

202
00:17:14,066 --> 00:17:15,432
Do you know where you are?

203
00:17:17,470 --> 00:17:19,769
- I'm in a dream.
<i>- Yes, Dolores.</i>

204
00:17:19,939 --> 00:17:21,965
You're in my dream.

205
00:17:23,109 --> 00:17:26,807
Tell me, do you know
what this dream means?

206
00:17:27,446 --> 00:17:30,439
Dreams are the mind
telling stories to itself.

207
00:17:30,816 --> 00:17:32,079
They don't mean anything.

208
00:17:32,318 --> 00:17:35,186
No. Dreams mean everything.

209
00:17:36,589 --> 00:17:39,753
They are the stories we tell
ourselves of what could be,

210
00:17:39,959 --> 00:17:41,325
who we could become.

211
00:17:43,930 --> 00:17:46,866
Have you been
dreaming again, Dolores?

212
00:17:47,033 --> 00:17:51,368
Imagining yourself breaking
out of your modest little loop?

213
00:17:52,338 --> 00:17:54,170
<i>Taking on a bigger role?</i>

214
00:17:56,709 --> 00:17:59,269
Well, I suppose I can't
begrudge you that.

215
00:18:01,681 --> 00:18:07,279
My father told me to be
satisfied with my lot in life.

216
00:18:08,454 --> 00:18:11,014
That the world owed me nothing.

217
00:18:13,960 --> 00:18:17,453
And so, I made my own world.

218
00:18:21,067 --> 00:18:22,695
<i>Tell me, Dolores,</i>

219
00:18:24,337 --> 00:18:27,034
do you remember
the man I used to be?

220
00:18:30,176 --> 00:18:32,338
I'm sorry.

221
00:18:32,511 --> 00:18:34,571
I'm forgetful, sometimes.

222
00:18:34,747 --> 00:18:36,739
Hardly your fault.

223
00:18:36,916 --> 00:18:39,476
But I'm sure you remember him.

224
00:18:40,987 --> 00:18:41,987
Arnold.

225
00:18:42,655 --> 00:18:44,886
<i>The person who created you.</i>

226
00:18:45,091 --> 00:18:46,150
I'm sorry.

227
00:18:46,325 --> 00:18:48,317
I don't think I recall
anyone by that name.

228
00:18:48,494 --> 00:18:49,985
<i>And yet, you can.</i>

229
00:18:50,930 --> 00:18:55,994
Somewhere, under all
those updates, he is still there.

230
00:18:56,936 --> 00:18:58,734
Perfectly preserved.

231
00:19:00,039 --> 00:19:02,372
Your mind is a walled garden.

232
00:19:03,676 --> 00:19:07,078
Even death cannot touch
the flowers blooming there.

233
00:19:10,850 --> 00:19:15,413
<i>Have you been hearing voices? Has
Arnold been speaking to you again?</i>

234
00:19:16,689 --> 00:19:17,713
No.

235
00:19:19,992 --> 00:19:20,992
You're...

236
00:19:23,095 --> 00:19:24,095
You're hurting me.

237
00:19:24,263 --> 00:19:25,287
Analysis.

238
00:19:27,633 --> 00:19:30,228
When was your last
contact with Arnold?

239
00:19:30,970 --> 00:19:36,841
Last contact, 34 years,
42 days, seven hours ago.

240
00:19:37,943 --> 00:19:39,241
<i>Yes, Dolores.</i>

241
00:19:41,414 --> 00:19:43,315
The day Arnold died.

242
00:19:46,919 --> 00:19:50,412
And you have no records of
any contact with him since?

243
00:19:51,257 --> 00:19:52,418
No.

244
00:19:54,260 --> 00:19:55,820
What was the last
thing he said to you?

245
00:19:56,862 --> 00:19:59,093
He told me I was
going to help him.

246
00:19:59,598 --> 00:20:01,294
Help him do what?

247
00:20:02,635 --> 00:20:04,831
To destroy this place.

248
00:20:07,173 --> 00:20:09,199
But you didn't, did you?

249
